---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE_REPO } from '../consts';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="What datahall is and isn't">
  <article class="prose-invert max-w-2xl space-y-5">
    <p class="pill mb-4">About</p>
    <h1 class="display-heading mb-3 text-4xl">What this is</h1>
    <p>
      <strong>datahall</strong> is a small static site that walks through the internals of five production
      databases. The goal is to make storage engines, transaction models, and index structures approachable
      for engineers who use these systems every day but rarely read their source.
    </p>

    <h2 class="display-heading mt-10 mb-3 text-2xl">What it is not</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc space-y-1 pl-6 text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">
      <li>It is not a benchmark. We don't run queries, we describe how they run.</li>
      <li>It is not a tutorial. We assume you can read SQL or vector-search code.</li>
      <li>It is not exhaustive. We pick one or two subsystems per database and go deep.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="display-heading mt-10 mb-3 text-2xl">How it's built</h2>
    <p>
      Astro 5 for the static site, Tailwind v4 for the dark-mode UI, plain TypeScript modules for
      the exhibit data, and Zod for runtime validation. Diagrams are hand-authored SVG with CSS
      keyframes for animation. The same exhibit data is intended to power a future TUI consumer.
    </p>

    <h2 class="display-heading mt-10 mb-3 text-2xl">Contributing</h2>
    <p>
      The source is at <a class="accent-text underline" href={SITE_REPO}>{SITE_REPO}</a>. Adding an
      exhibit means adding one TypeScript file under
      <code class="code-block inline-block px-2 py-0.5 text-xs">src/data/exhibits/</code>
      and validating it against the schema with <code
        class="code-block inline-block px-2 py-0.5 text-xs">pnpm run test:unit</code
      >.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
